# Migrations

Migrations are defined in db/migrations

All tables/types added in the up function must be dropped in reverse order in the down function.

Generally speaking use createStandardTable.

# It's okay to modify migrations

Our project has no live users yet so it's preferred to modify migrations to have a single source of truth for table definitions.

So if you are wanting to modify a table defined in db/migrations/20240108094046_some_table.ts
you would run

```bash
$ deno task docker db:migrate past db/migrations/20240108094046_some_table.ts
```

Then do your modifications to that file (because the up/down may change). If any seeds need updating, update those then run

```bash
$ deno task docker db:rebuild
```

This will generate a new db.d.ts with updated type definitions which will make continuing with your migration easier as you'll be able to run 

```bash
$ deno task check
```

To see type errors before proceeding further with your plan. It's expected you get type errors at this stage, but if the columns didn't get added how you'd expect in db.d.ts then abort.